[src:hunting/40-s-w] The **.40 S&W** is a rimless pistol cartridge developed jointly by American firearms manufacturers Smith & Wesson and Winchester in 1990.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W was developed as a law enforcement cartridge designed to duplicate the performance of the Federal Bureau of Investigation's (FBI) reduced-velocity 10mm Auto cartridge which could be retrofitted into medium-frame (9 mm size) semi-automatic handguns.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] It uses 0.40-inch-diameter (10 mm) bullets typically ranging in weight from 105 to 200 grains (6.8 to 13.0 g).
[src:hunting/40-s-w] In the aftermath of the 1986 FBI Miami shootout, in which two FBI special agents were killed and five wounded, the FBI started the process of testing 9×19mm Parabellum and .45 ACP ammunition in preparation to replace its standard-issue revolver with a semi-automatic pistol.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The semi-automatic pistol offered two advantages over the revolver: increased ammunition capacity and increased ease of reloading during a gunfight.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The FBI was satisfied with the performance of its .38 Special +P 158 gr (10.2 g) lead semi-wadcutter hollowpoint (LSWCHP) cartridge ("FBI load") based on decades of dependable performance.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Ammunition for the new semi-automatic pistol had to deliver terminal performance equal or superior to the .38 Special FBI load.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The FBI developed a series of practically oriented tests involving eight test events that they believed reasonably represented the kinds of situations that FBI agents commonly encountered in shooting incidents.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] During tests of the 9×19mm and .45 ACP ammunition, the unit chief of the FBI Firearms Training Unit, John Hall, decided to include tests of the 10mm Auto cartridge, supplying his own Colt Delta Elite 10mm semi-automatic, and personally hand-loaded ammunition.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The FBI's tests revealed that a 170–180 gr (11.0–11.7 g) JHP 10mm bullet, propelled between 900–1,000 ft/s (270–300 m/s), achieved desired terminal performance without the heavy recoil associated with conventional 10mm ammunition (1,300–1,400 ft/s (400–430 m/s)).
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The FBI contacted Smith & Wesson and requested that it design a handgun to FBI specifications, based on the existing large-frame Smith & Wesson Model 4506 .45 ACP handgun, that would reliably function with the FBI's reduced-velocity 10mm ammunition.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] During this collaboration with the FBI, S&W realized that downsizing the 10mm full-power to meet the FBI's medium-velocity specification meant less powder and more airspace in the case.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] They found that by removing the airspace they could shorten the 10mm case enough to fit within their medium-frame 9mm handguns and load it with a 180 gr (11.7 g) JHP bullet to produce ballistic performance identical to the FBI's reduced-velocity 10mm cartridge.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] S&W then teamed with Winchester to produce a new cartridge, the .40 S&W.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] It uses a small pistol primer whereas the 10mm cartridge uses a large pistol primer.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W cartridge debuted January 17, 1990, along with the new Smith & Wesson Model 4006 pistol, although it was several months before the pistols were available for purchase.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Austrian manufacturer Glock Ges.m.b.H. were commercially available ahead of Smith & Wesson in 1990, with pistols chambered in .40 S&W (the Glock 22 and Glock 23) which were announced a week before the 4006.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Glock's rapid introduction was aided by its engineering of a pistol chambered in 10mm Auto, the Glock 20, only a short time earlier.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Since the .40 S&W uses the same bore diameter and case head as the 10mm Auto, it was merely a matter of adapting the 10mm design to the shorter 9×19mm Parabellum frames.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The new guns and ammunition were an immediate success, and pistols in the new caliber were adopted by several law enforcement agencies around the nation, including the FBI, which adopted the Glock pistol in .40 S&W in May 1997.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The popularity of the .40 S&W accelerated with the passage of the now-expired Federal Assault Weapons Ban of 1994, which prohibited sales of pistol or rifle magazines that could hold more than ten cartridges, regardless of caliber.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Several U.S. states, and a number of local governments, also banned or regulated so-called "high-capacity" magazines.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] As a result, many new firearm buyers limited to purchasing pistols with a maximum magazine capacity of 10 rounds chose pistols in the .40 S&W chambering instead of smaller-diameter cartridges such as the 9×19mm (9mm Luger or 9mm Parabellum).
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W case length and overall cartridge length are shortened, but other dimensions except for case web and wall thickness remain identical to the 10mm Auto.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Both cartridges headspace on the mouth of the case.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Thus in a semi-auto, they are not interchangeable.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Fired from a 10mm semi-auto, the .40 Smith & Wesson cartridge will headspace on the extractor and the bullet will jump a 0.142 inches (3.6 mm) freebore just like a .38 Special fired from a .357 Magnum revolver.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] If the cartridge is not held by the extractor, the chances for a ruptured primer are great.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Smith & Wesson does make a double-action revolver (the Model 610) that can fire either cartridge via use of moon clips.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] A single-action revolver in the .38–40 chambering can also fire .40 or 10mm rounds provided it is equipped with a correctly sized cylinder.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Some .40 caliber handguns can be converted to 9mm with a special purpose-made barrel, magazine change, and other parts.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] In 2015, the FBI announced they were going back to 9mm ammunition, citing advancements in ballistic technology and increased accuracy in a gunfight.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The FBI also found that .40 S&W rounds were causing excessive wear on pistols and were harder to control for some agents.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] This has caused a substantial contribution to the .40 S&W's decline in popularity with law enforcement in the US.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W has a 1.25 ml (19.3 gr H2O) cartridge case capacity.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The common rifling twist rate for this cartridge is 406 millimetres (16.0 in), with 6 grooves, land diameter 9.91 mm, groove diameter 10.17 mm, and land width 3.05 mm, and the primer type is small pistol.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] According to the official C.I.P. guidelines, the .40 S&W case can handle up to 225 MPa (32,600 psi) piezo pressure.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] In C.I.P.-regulated countries, every pistol/cartridge combo has to be proofed at 130% of this maximum C.I.P. pressure to certify for sale to consumers.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The SAAMI pressure limit for the .40 S&W is set at 241.32 MPa (35,001 psi) piezo pressure.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W cartridge has been popular with law enforcement agencies in the United States, Canada, Australia, and Brazil.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] While possessing nearly identical accuracy, drift and drop as the 9mm Parabellum, it has an energy advantage over the 9mm Parabellum and .45 ACP, and a more manageable recoil than the 10mm Auto cartridge.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Marshall & Sanow (and other hydrostatic shock proponents) contend that with good jacketed hollow point bullets, the more energetic loads for the .40 S&W can also create hydrostatic shock in human-sized living targets.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Based on the ideal terminal ballistic performance in ordnance gelatin during lab testing in the late 1980s and early 1990s, the .40 S&W earned status as "the ideal cartridge for personal defense and law enforcement".
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Ballistically the .40 S&W is almost identical to the .38-40 Winchester introduced in 1874, as they share the same bullet diameter and bullet weight, and have similar muzzle velocities.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The energy of the .40 S&W exceeds standard-pressure .45 ACP loadings, generating between 350 foot-pounds (470 J) and 500 foot-pounds (680 J) of energy, depending on bullet weight.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Both the .40 S&W and the 9mm Parabellum operate at a 35,000 pounds per square inch (240 MPa) SAAMI maximum, compared to a 21,000 pounds per square inch (140 MPa) maximum for .45 ACP.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] .40 S&W pistols with standard (not extended) double-stack magazines can hold as many as 16 cartridges.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] While not displacing the 9mm Parabellum, the .40 S&W is commonly used in law enforcement applications in keeping with its origin with the FBI.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Select U.S. special operations units have available the .40 S&W and .45 ACP for their pistols.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The United States Coast Guard, having dual duties as maritime law enforcement and military deployments, has adopted the SIG Sauer P229R DAK in .40 S&W as their standard sidearm.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] However, as of 2020, the Coast Guard has adopted the Glock 19 GEN5 MOS as its new sidearm.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Numerous federal and local law enforcement agencies are currently in the process of transitioning from .40 S&W to 9mm, most notably the FBI, who adopted 9mm firearms in 2015.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Customs and Border Protection adopted 9mm Glock handguns, replacing the .40 S&W Heckler & Koch P2000 CBP was previously using.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W was originally loaded at subsonic velocity (984.25 ft/s (300.00 m/s)) with a 180 grains (11.7 g) bullet.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Since its introduction, various loads have been created, with the majority being either 155, 165 or 180 gr (10.0, 10.7 or 11.7 g).
[src:hunting/40-s-w] However, there are some bullets with weights as light as 135 gr (8.7 g) and as heavy as 200 gr (13.0 g).
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Cor-Bon and Winchester both offer a 135 gr (8.7 g) JHP and Cor-Bon also offers a 140 gr (9.1 g) Barnes XPB hollow-point.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The .40 S&W has been noted in a number of cartridge case failures involving older Glock pistols, due to the relatively large area of unsupported case head in those barrels, given its allowed chamber pressure level.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] The feed ramp on the Glock .40 S&W pistols is larger than on other Glocks, which leaves the rear bottom of the case unsupported, and it is in this unsupported area that the cases fail.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Most, but not all, of the failures have occurred with reloaded or remanufactured ammunition.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] Cartridges loaded at or above the SAAMI pressure, or slightly oversized cases which fire slightly out of battery are often considered to be the cause of these failures, which are commonly referred to as "kaBooms" or "kB!" for short.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] While these case failures do not often injure the person holding the pistol, the venting of high-pressure gas tends to eject the magazine out of the magazine well in a spectacular fashion, and usually destroys the pistol.
[src:hunting/40-s-w] In some cases, the barrel will also fail, blowing the top of the chamber off.
[src:hunting/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:hunting/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:hunting/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:hunting/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:hunting/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:hunting/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The book was reviewed in contemporary periodicals including the *London Medical Gazette*, *The Athenaeum*, and *The Veterinary Record*.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] It was later noted by writers including Henry S.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Ralph Fletcher (1780—1851) was a surgeon based in Gloucester.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He studied at St Bartholomew's Hospital in London and received an M.D. from the University of Edinburgh Medical School.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He held appointments at the Gloucester Infirmary, Dispensary, and Lunatic Asylum.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He published medical papers on the relation between mental and physical health.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher was twice elected Mayor of Gloucester and served as president of the local branch of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He lived on Barton Street, near the city's animal pound, and his observations of the animals kept there were said to have inspired *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals*.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In a brief "Preliminary Note", Fletcher writes about the suffering of animals, especially those dependent on humans.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He rejects the view that animals are insensible to pain or that their suffering is divinely ordained, and argues for compassion on moral and theological grounds.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In "Importance of the Subject", Fletcher draws on his experience as president of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes that public acts of cruelty form only a small part of a wider problem, and that abuse often takes place in private spaces such as stables, slaughterhouses, and homes.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He argues that existing legislation was inadequate, because small fines and judicial discretion to reduce sentences did not deter offenders.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The main part of the book consists of notes on individual animals and practices.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher describes donkeys as animals commonly subjected to overwork and neglect.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He condemns blood sports such as shooting tied cocks and badger-baiting.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] His discussion of cats and dogs contrasts their treatment: he writes that cats were often tormented or killed for amusement, while dogs suffered from starvation, beatings, cart-work, and fighting.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher criticises methods used in the rearing and slaughter of calves and lambs, including starvation and repeated bleeding to produce white veal.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes about overwork, neglect, and abandonment, and argues that owners as well as drivers should be held legally responsible.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher ends by calling for tougher penalties for cruelty, official oversight of slaughterhouses and stables, wider public instruction in humane treatment, and hospitals for sick and injured animals.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] A review in the *London Medical Gazette* described the book as the work of a hospital surgeon acquainted with suffering.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The reviewer agreed with Fletcher's criticism of animal experimentation, but called his proposal for hospitals for animals a "somewhat Utopian scheme" said to have some precedent in the East.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Salt in the "Bibliography of Animal Rights" section of his 1892 work *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress*, where he referred to it as a treatise on animal cruelty.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In his 1989 reference work *Keyguide to Information Sources in Animal Rights*, Charles R.
[src:hunting/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Magel described *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals* as an early account of animal abuse in the Gloucester area and noted its proposal for hospitals for animals modelled on human institutions.
[src:hunting/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:hunting/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:hunting/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:hunting/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:hunting/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:hunting/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:hunting/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:hunting/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:hunting/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:hunting/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Recreationally hunted species are generally referred to as the *game*, and are usually mammals and birds.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] A person participating in a hunt is a **hunter** or (less commonly) **huntsman**; a natural area used for hunting is called a game reserve; and an experienced hunter who helps organise a hunt and/or manage the game reserve is also known as a gamekeeper.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting activities by humans arose in *Homo erectus* or earlier, in the order of millions of years ago.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting has become deeply embedded in various human cultures and was once an important part of rural economies—classified by economists as part of primary production alongside forestry, agriculture, and fishery.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Modern regulations (see game law) distinguish lawful hunting activities from illegal poaching, which involves the unauthorised and unregulated killing, trapping, or capture of animals.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Apart from food provision, hunting can be a means of population control.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] However, excessive hunting has also heavily contributed to the endangerment, extirpation and extinction of many animals.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Some animal rights and anti-hunting activists regard hunting as a cruel, perverse and unnecessary blood sport.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Certain hunting practices, such as canned hunts and trophy tours (especially to poor countries), are considered unethical and exploitative even by some hunters.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Marine mammals such as whales and pinnipeds are also targets of hunting, both recreationally and commercially, often with heated controversies regarding the morality, ethics and legality of such practices.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The pursuit, harvesting or catch and release of fish and aquatic cephalopods and crustaceans is called fishing, which however is widely accepted and not commonly categorised as a form of hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] It is also not considered hunting to pursue animals without intent to kill them, as in wildlife photography, birdwatching, or scientific-research activities which involve tranquilizing or tagging of animals, although green hunting is still called so.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The practices of netting or trapping insects and other arthropods for trophy collection, or the foraging or gathering of plants and mushrooms, are also not regarded as hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Skillful tracking and acquisition of an elusive target has caused the word *hunt* to be used in the vernacular as a metaphor for searching and obtaining something, as in "treasure hunting", "bargain hunting", "hunting for votes" and even "hunting down" corruption and waste.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The word *hunt* serves as both a noun ("the act, the practice, or an instance of hunting") and a verb ("to pursue for food or in sport").
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The noun has been dated to the early 12th century, from the verb *hunt*.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The meaning of "a body of persons associated for the purpose of hunting with a pack of hounds" is first recorded in the 1570s.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] "The act of searching for someone or something" is from about 1600.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The general sense of "search diligently" (for anything) is first recorded c.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] It predates the emergence of *Homo sapiens* (anatomically modern humans) and may even predate the genus *Homo*.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The oldest undisputed evidence for hunting dates to the Early Pleistocene, consistent with the emergence and early dispersal of *Homo erectus* about 1.7 million years ago (Acheulean).
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] There is no direct evidence for hunting predating *Homo erectus*, in either *Homo habilis* or in *Australopithecus*.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The early hominid ancestors of humans were probably frugivores or omnivores, with a partially carnivorous diet from scavenging rather than hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Evidence for australopithecine meat consumption was presented in the 1990s.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The common chimpanzee (*Pan troglodytes*) regularly engages in troop predation behaviour, where bands of beta males are led by an alpha male.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Bonobos (*Pan paniscus*) have also been observed to occasionally engage in group hunting, although more rarely than *Pan troglodytes*, mainly subsisting on a frugivorous diet.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Indirect evidence for Oldowan era hunting, by early *Homo* or late *Australopithecus*, has been presented in a 2009 study based on an Oldowan site in southwestern Kenya.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Louis Binford (1986) criticised the idea that early hominids and early humans were hunters.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Stone spearheads dated as early as 500,000 years ago were found in South Africa.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Wood does not preserve well, however, and Craig Stanford, a primatologist and professor of anthropology at the University of Southern California, has suggested that the discovery of spear use by chimpanzees probably means that early humans used wooden spears as well, perhaps, five million years ago.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The earliest dated find of surviving wooden hunting spears dates to the very end of the Lower Paleolithic, about 300,000 years ago.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The Schöningen spears, found in 1976 in Germany, are associated with *Homo heidelbergensis*.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The hunting hypothesis sees the emergence of behavioral modernity in the Middle Paleolithic as directly related to hunting, including mating behaviour, the establishment of language, culture, and religion, mythology and animal sacrifice.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] However, 9000-year-old remains of a female hunter along with a toolkit of projectile points and animal processing implements were discovered at the Andean site of Wilamaya Patjxa, Puno District in Peru.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Early humans progressively invented tools and techniques for trapping animals.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The earliest spears were crafted from wood, with tips toughened by burning.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] By 15,000 BC, hunters employed wooden and bone spear-launchers to enhance force and distance.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] These devices were frequently adorned with carvings of creatures.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Evidence exists that hunting may have been one of the multiple, or possibly main, environmental factors leading to the Holocene extinction of megafauna and their replacement by smaller herbivores.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Humans are thought to have played a very significant role in the extinction of the Australian megafauna that was widespread prior to human occupation.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting was a crucial component of hunter-gatherer societies before the domestication of livestock and the dawn of agriculture, beginning about 11,000 years ago in some parts of the world.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In addition to the spear, hunting weapons developed during the Upper Paleolithic include the atlatl (a spear-thrower; before 30,000 years ago) and the bow (18,000 years ago).
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] By the Mesolithic, hunting strategies had diversified with the development of these more far-reaching weapons and the domestication of the dog about 15,000 years ago.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Evidence puts the earliest known mammoth hunting in Asia with spears to approximately 16,200 years ago.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Many species of animals have been hunted throughout history.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] One theory is that in North America and Eurasia, caribou and wild reindeer "may well be the species of single greatest importance in the entire anthropological literature on hunting" (see also Reindeer Age), although the varying importance of different species depended on the geographic location.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Mesolithic hunter-gathering lifestyles remained prevalent in some parts of the Americas, Sub-Saharan Africa, and Siberia, as well as all of Australia, until the European Age of Discovery.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] They still persist in some tribal societies, albeit in rapid decline.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In Africa, one of the last remaining hunter-gatherer tribes are the Hadza of Tanzania.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Even as animal domestication became relatively widespread and after the development of agriculture, hunting usually remained a significant contributor to the human food-supply.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The supplementary meat and materials from hunting included protein, bone for implements, sinew for cordage, fur, feathers, rawhide and leather used in clothing.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting is still vital in marginal climates, especially those unsuited for pastoral uses or for agriculture.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] For example, Inuit in the Arctic trap and hunt animals for clothing and use the skins of sea mammals to make kayaks, clothing, and footwear.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] On ancient reliefs, especially from Mesopotamia, kings are often depicted by sculptors as hunters of big game such as lions and are often portrayed hunting from a war chariot - early examples of royalty symbolically and militaristically engaging in hunting as "the sport of kings".
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The cultural and psychological importance of hunting in ancient societies is represented by deities such as the horned god Cernunnos and lunar goddesses of classical antiquity, the Greek Artemis or Roman Diana.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Taboos are often related to hunting, and mythological association of prey species with a divinity could be reflected in hunting restrictions such as a reserve surrounding a temple.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Euripides' tale of Artemis and Actaeon, for example, may be seen as a caution against disrespect of prey or against impudent boasting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] With the domestication of the dog, birds of prey, and the ferret, various forms of animal-aided hunting developed, including venery (scent-hound hunting, such as fox hunting), coursing (sight-hound hunting), falconry, and ferreting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] While these are all associated with medieval hunting, over time, various dog breeds were selected by humans for very precise tasks during the hunt, reflected in such names as "pointer" and "setter".
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Even as agriculture and animal husbandry became more prevalent, hunting often remained as a part of human culture where the environment and social conditions allowed.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunter-gatherer societies persisted, even when increasingly confined to marginal areas.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] And within agricultural systems, hunting served to kill animals that prey upon domestic and wild animals or to attempt to extirpate animals seen by humans as competition for resources such as water or forage.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The meaning of the word *game* in Middle English evolved to include an animal which is hunted.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] As the domestication of animals for meat grew, subsistence hunting remained among the lowest classes; however, the stylised pursuit of game in European societies became a luxury.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Dangerous hunting, such as for lions or wild boars, often done on horseback or from a chariot, had a function similar to tournaments and manly sports.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting ranked as an honourable, somewhat competitive pastime to help the aristocracy practice skills of war in times of peace.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In most parts of medieval Europe, the upper class obtained the sole rights to hunt in certain areas of a feudal territory.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Game in these areas was used as a source of food and furs, often provided via professional huntsmen, but it was also expected to provide a form of recreation for the aristocracy.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The importance of this proprietary view of game can be seen in the Robin Hood legends, in which one of the primary charges against the outlaws is that they "hunt the King's deer".
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In contrast, settlers in Anglophone colonies gloried democratically in hunting for all.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In medieval Europe, hunting was considered by Johannes Scotus Eriugena to be part of the set of *seven mechanical arts*.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Although various other animals have been used to aid the hunter, such as ferrets, the dog has assumed many very important uses to the hunter.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The domestication of the dog has led to a symbiotic relationship in which the dog's independence from humans is deferred.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Though dogs can survive independently of humans, and in many cases do ferally, when raised or adopted by humans the species tends to defer to its control in exchange for habitation, food and support.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Dogs today are used to find, chase, retrieve, and sometimes kill game.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Dogs allow humans to pursue and kill prey that would otherwise be very difficult or dangerous to hunt.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Different breeds of specifically bred hunting dog are used for different types of hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Waterfowl are commonly hunted using retrieving dogs such as the Labrador Retriever, the Golden Retriever, the Chesapeake Bay Retriever, the Brittany Spaniel, and other similar breeds.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Game birds are flushed out using flushing spaniels such as the English Springer Spaniel, the various Cocker Spaniels and similar breeds.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The hunting of wild mammals in England and Wales with dogs was banned under the Hunting Act 2004.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The wild mammals include fox, hare, deer and mink.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] There are, however, exceptions in the Act.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Nevertheless, there have been numerous attempts on behalf of activists, pressure groups, etc. to revoke the act over the last two decades.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Many prehistoric deities are depicted as predators or prey of humans, often in a zoomorphic form, perhaps alluding to the importance of hunting for most Palaeolithic cultures.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In many pagan religions, specific rituals are conducted before or after a hunt; the rituals done may vary according to the species hunted or the season the hunt is taking place.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Often a hunting ground, or the hunt for one or more species, was reserved or prohibited in the context of a temple cult.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In Roman religion, Diana is the goddess of the hunt.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hindu scriptures describe hunting as an occupation, as well as a sport of the kingly.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Even figures considered divine are described to have engaged in hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] One of the names of the god Shiva is Mrigavyadha (deer-slayer).
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The word *Mriga*, in many Indian languages including Malayalam, not only stands for deer, but for all animals and animal instincts (Mriga Thrishna).
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Shiva, as Mrigavyadha, is the one who destroys the animal instincts in human beings.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In the epic Ramayana, Dasharatha, the father of Rama, is said to have the ability to hunt in the dark.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] During one of his hunting expeditions, he accidentally killed Shravana, mistaking him for game.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] During Rama's exile in the forest, Ravana kidnapped his wife, Sita, from their hut, while Rama was asked by Sita to capture a golden deer, and his brother Lakshman went after him.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] According to the Mahabharat, Pandu, the father of the Pandavas, accidentally killed the sage Kindama and his wife with an arrow, mistaking them for a deer.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Jainism teaches followers to have tremendous respect for all of life.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Prohibitions for hunting and meat eating are the fundamental conditions for being a Jain.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Buddhism's first precept is the respect for all sentient life.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The general approach by all Buddhists is to avoid killing any living animals.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In Sikhism, only meat obtained from hunting, or slaughtered with the Jhatka is permitted.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The Sikh gurus, especially Guru Hargobind and Guru Gobind Singh were ardent hunters.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Many old Sikh Rehatnamas like Prem Sumarag, recommend hunting wild boar and deer.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] However, among modern Sikhs, the practice of hunting has died down; some even saying that all meat is forbidden.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] From early Christian times, hunting has been forbidden to Roman Catholic Church clerics.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] XXIV, De reform., c. xii), which seems to imply that not all hunting is illicit, and canonists generally make a distinction declaring noisy (*clamorosa*) hunting unlawful, but not quiet (*quieta*) hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Ferraris gives it as the general sense of canonists that hunting is allowed to clerics if it be indulged in rarely and for sufficient cause, as necessity, utility or "honest" recreation, and with that moderation which is becoming to the ecclesiastical state.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Ziegler, however, thinks that the interpretation of the canonists is not in accordance with the letter or spirit of the laws of the church.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Nevertheless, although a distinction between lawful and unlawful hunting is undoubtedly permissible, it is certain that a bishop can absolutely prohibit all hunting to the clerics of his diocese, as was done by synods at Milan, Avignon, Liège, Cologne, and elsewhere.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Benedict XIV declared that such synodal decrees are not too severe, as an absolute prohibition of hunting is more conformable to the ecclesiastical law.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In practice, therefore, the synodal statutes of various localities must be consulted to discover whether they allow quiet hunting or prohibit it altogether.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Small-scale hunting as a family or subsistence farming activity is recognised by Pope Francis in his encyclical letter, Laudato si', as a legitimate and valuable aspect of employment within the food production system.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting is not forbidden in Jewish law, although there is an aversion to it.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The great 18th-century authority Rabbi Yechezkel Landau after a study concluded although "hunting would not be considered cruelty to animals insofar as the animal is generally killed quickly and not tortured...
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] There is an unseemly element in it, namely cruelty." The other issue is that hunting can be dangerous and Judaism places an extreme emphasis on the value of human life.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Islamic Sharia Law permits hunting of lawful animals and birds if they cannot be easily caught and slaughtered.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] However, this is only for the purpose of food and not for trophy hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] A safari, from a Swahili word meaning "journey, expedition," especially in Africa, is defined as a journey to see or kill animals in their natural environment, most commonly in East Africa.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Safari as a distinctive way of hunting was popularized by the US author Ernest Hemingway and President Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] A safari may consist of a several-days—or even weeks-long journey, with camping in the bush or jungle, while pursuing big game.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Nowadays, it is often used to describe hunting tours through African wildlife.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunters are usually tourists, accompanied by licensed and highly regulated professional hunters, local guides, skinners, and porters in more difficult terrains.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] A special safari type is the solo-safari, where all the license acquiring, stalking, preparation, and outfitting is done by the hunter himself.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] During the feudal and colonial times in British India, hunting or *shikar* was regarded as a regal sport in the numerous princely states, as many maharajas and nawabs, as well as British officers, maintained a whole corps of *shikari*s (big-game hunters), who were native professional hunters.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] They would be headed by a master of the hunt, who might be styled *mir-shikar*.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Often, they recruited the normally low-ranking local tribes because of their traditional knowledge of the environment and hunting techniques.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Big game, such as Bengal tigers, might be hunted from the back of an Indian elephant.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Regional social norms are generally antagonistic to hunting, while a few sects, such as the Bishnoi, lay special emphasis on the conservation of particular species, such as the antelope.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] India's Wildlife Protection Act of 1972 bans the killing of all wild animals.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] However, the Chief Wildlife Warden may, if satisfied that any wild animal from a specified list has become dangerous to human life or is so disabled or diseased as to be beyond recovery, permit any person to hunt such an animal.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In this case, the body of any wild animal killed or wounded becomes government property.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The term was used in the nineteenth century, and had become common usage by the First World War.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Unarmed fox hunting on horseback with hounds is the type of hunting most closely associated with the United Kingdom; in fact, "hunting" without qualification implies fox hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] What in other countries is called "hunting" is called "shooting" (birds) or "stalking" (deer) in Britain.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Fox hunting is a social activity for the upper classes, with roles strictly defined by wealth and status.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Similar to fox hunting in many ways is the chasing of hares with hounds.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Pairs of sighthounds (or long-dogs), such as greyhounds, may be used to pursue a hare in coursing, where the greyhounds are marked as to their skill in coursing the hare (but are not intended to actually catch it), or the hare may be pursued with scent hounds such as beagles or harriers.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Other sorts of foxhounds may also be used for hunting stags (deer) or mink.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Deer stalking with rifles is carried out on foot without hounds, using stealth.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] These forms of hunting have been controversial in the UK.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Animal welfare supporters believe that hunting causes unnecessary suffering to foxes, horses, and hounds.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Proponents argue that the activity is a historical tradition.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Using dogs to chase wild mammals was made illegal in February 2005 by the Hunting Act 2004; there were a number of exemptions (under which the activity may not be illegal) in the act for hunting with hounds, but no exemptions at all for hare-coursing.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Game birds, especially pheasants and red grouse, are shot with shotguns for sport in the UK; the British Association for Shooting and Conservation says that over a million people per year participate in shooting, including game shooting, clay pigeon shooting, and target shooting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Shooting as practiced in Britain, as opposed to traditional hunting, requires little questing for game—around thirty-five million birds are released onto shooting estates every year, some having been factory farmed.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Shoots can be elaborate affairs with guns placed in assigned positions and assistants to help load shotguns.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] When in position, "beaters" move through the areas of cover, swinging sticks or flags to drive the game out.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Such events are often called "drives," "driven hunting," or "driven hunts" (e.g., driven grouse shooting).
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The open season for grouse in the UK begins on 12 August, the so-called Glorious Twelfth.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The definition of game in the United Kingdom is governed by the Game Act 1831 (1 & 2 Will.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] A similar tradition, *ojeo*, exists in Spain.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] North American hunting pre-dates the United States by thousands of years and was an important part of many pre-Columbian Native American cultures.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Native Americans retain some hunting rights and are exempt from some laws as part of Indian treaties and otherwise under federal law—examples include eagle feather laws and exemptions in the Marine Mammal Protection Act.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] This is considered particularly important in Alaskan native communities.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Gun usage in hunting is typically regulated by game category, area within the state, and time period.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Regulations for big-game hunting often specify a minimum caliber or muzzle energy for firearms.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The use of rifles is often banned for safety reasons in areas with high population densities or limited topographic relief.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Regulations may also limit or ban the use of lead in ammunition because of environmental concerns.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Specific seasons for bow hunting or muzzle-loading black-powder guns are often established to limit competition with hunters using more effective weapons.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting in the United States is not associated with any particular class or culture; a 2006 poll showed seventy-eight per cent of Americans supported legal hunting, although relatively few Americans actually hunt.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] At the beginning of the 21st century, just six per cent of Americans hunted.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting in other areas of the country fell below the national average.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Overall, in the 1996–2006 period, the number of hunters over the age of sixteen declined by ten per cent, a drop attributable to a number of factors including habitat loss and changes in recreation habits.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The principles of the fair chase have been a part of the American hunting tradition for over one hundred years.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The role of the hunter-conservationist, popularised by Theodore Roosevelt, and perpetuated by Roosevelt's formation of the Boone and Crockett Club, has been central to the development of the modern fair chase tradition.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] When Internet hunting was introduced in 2005, allowing people to hunt over the Internet using remotely controlled guns, the practice was widely criticised by hunters as violating the principles of fair chase.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] As a representative of the National Rifle Association of America (NRA) explained, "The NRA has always maintained that fair chase, being in the field with your firearm or bow, is an important element of hunting tradition.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Animals such as blackbuck, nilgai, axis deer, fallow deer, zebras, barasingha, gazelle and many other exotic game species can now be found on game farms and ranches in Texas, where they were introduced for sport hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] These hunters can be found paying in excess of $10,000 to take trophy animals on these controlled ranches.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The Russian imperial hunts evolved from hunting traditions of early Russian rulers—Grand Princes and Tsars—under the influence of hunting customs of European royal courts.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The imperial hunts were organised mainly in Peterhof, Tsarskoye Selo, and Gatchina.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting in Australia has evolved around the hunting and eradication of various animals considered to be pests or invasive species .
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] All native animals are protected by law, and certain species such as kangaroos and ducks can be hunted by licensed shooters but only under a special permit on public lands during open seasons.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The introduced species that are targeted include European rabbits, red foxes, deer (sambar, hog, red, fallow, chital and rusa), feral cats, pigs, goats, brumbies, donkeys and occasionally camels, as well as introduced upland birds such as quails, pheasants and partridges.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] New Zealand has a strong hunting culture.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] When humans arrived, the only mammals present on the islands making up New Zealand were bats, although seals and other marine mammals were present along the coasts.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] However, when humans arrived they brought other species with them.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Polynesian voyagers introduced kuri (dogs), kiore (Polynesian rats), as well as a range of plant species.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] European explorers further added to New Zealand's biota, particularly pigs which were introduced by either Captain Cook or the French explorer De Surville in the 1700s.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] During the nineteenth century, as European colonisation took place, acclimatisation societies were established.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The societies introduced a large number of species with no use other than as prey for hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Species that adapted well to the New Zealand terrain include deer, pigs, goats, hare, tahr and chamois.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] With wilderness areas, suitable forage, and no natural predators, their populations exploded.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Government agencies view the animals as pests due to their effects on the natural environment and on agricultural production, but hunters view them as a resource.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Iranian tradition regarded hunting as an essential part of a prince's education, and hunting was well recorded for the education of the upper-class youths during pre-Islamic Persia.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] As of October 2020, a hunting licensee costs $20,000.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The Department of Environment although do not report the number of permits issued.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The numbers of licensed hunters in Japan, including those using snares and guns, is generally decreasing, while their average age is increasing.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] As of 2010, there were approximately 190,000 registered hunters, approximately 65% of whom were sixty years old or older.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] There is a very active tradition of hunting small to medium-sized wild game in Trinidad and Tobago.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting is carried out with firearms, slingshots and cage traps, and sometimes aided by the use of hounds.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The illegal use of trap guns and snare nets also occurs.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] With approximately 12,000 to 13,000 hunters applying for and being granted hunting permits in recent years, there is some concern that the practice might not be sustainable.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In addition, there are at present no bag limits and the open season is comparatively very long (5 months – October to February inclusive).
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] As such hunting pressure from legal hunters is very high.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Added to that, there is a thriving and very lucrative black market for poached wild game (sold and enthusiastically purchased as expensive luxury delicacies) and the numbers of commercial poachers in operation is unknown but presumed to be fairly high.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] It appears that the red brocket deer population has been extirpated in Tobago as a result of over-hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] By some time in the mid 20th century another extirpation due to over-hunting occurred in Trinidad with its population of horned screamer (a large game bird).
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Various herons, ducks, doves, the green iguana, the cryptic golden tegu, the spectacled caiman, the common opossum and the capybara are also commonly hunted and poached.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] There is also some poaching of 'fully protected species', including red howler monkey and capuchin monkeys, southern tamandua, Brazilian porcupine, yellow-footed tortoise, the critically endangered island endemic Trinidad piping guan and even one of the national birds, the scarlet ibis.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Legal hunters pay relatively small fees to obtain hunting licenses and undergo no official basic conservation biology or hunting-ethics/fair chase training and are not assessed regarding their knowledge and comprehension of the local wildlife conservation laws.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] There is presumed to be relatively little subsistence hunting in the country (with most hunting for either sport or commercial profit).
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The local wildlife management authorities are under-staffed and under-funded, and as such little in the way of enforcement is done to uphold existing wildlife management laws, with hunting/poaching occurring both in and out of season and even in wildlife sanctuaries.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] There is some indication that the government is beginning to take the issue of wildlife management more seriously, with well drafted legislation being brought before Parliament in 2015.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting is claimed to give resource managers an important tool in managing populations that might exceed the carrying capacity of their habitat and threaten the well-being of other species, or, in some instances, damage human health or safety.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In some cases, hunting actually can increase the population of predators such as coyotes by removing territorial bounds that would otherwise be established, resulting in excess neighbouring migrations into an area, thus artificially increasing the population.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting advocates assert that hunting reduces intraspecific competition for food and shelter, reducing mortality among the remaining animals.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Some environmentalists assert that (re)introducing predators would achieve the same end with greater efficiency and less negative effect, such as introducing significant amounts of free lead into the environment and food chain.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In the United States, wildlife managers are frequently part of hunting regulatory and licensing bodies, where they help to set rules on the number, manner and conditions in which game may be hunted.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Management agencies sometimes rely on hunting to control specific animal populations, as has been the case with deer in North America.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] These hunts may sometimes be carried out by professional shooters, although others may include amateur hunters.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Many US city and local governments hire professional and amateur hunters each year to reduce populations of animals such as deer that are becoming hazardous in a restricted area, such as neighbourhood parks and metropolitan open spaces.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] A large part of managing populations involves managing the number and, sometimes, the size or age of animals harvested so as to ensure the sustainability of the population.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Tools that are frequently used to control harvest are bag limits and season closures, although gear restrictions such as archery-only seasons are becoming increasingly popular in an effort to reduce hunter success rates in countries that rely on bag limits per hunter instead of per area.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Illegal hunting and harvesting of wild species contrary to local and international conservation and wildlife management laws is called poaching.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Game preservation is one of the tactics used to prevent poaching.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Violations of hunting laws and regulations involving poaching are normally punishable by law.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Punishment can include confiscation of equipment, fines or a prison sentence.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The right to hunt—sometimes in combination with the right to fish—is protected implicitly, as a consequence of the right of ownership, or explicitly, as a right on its own, in a number of jurisdictions.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] For instance, as of 2019, a total of 22 U.S. states explicitly recognize a subjective right to hunt in their constitutions.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Bag limits are provisions under the law that control how many animals of a given species or group of species can be killed, although there are often species for which bag limits do not apply.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] There are also jurisdictions where bag limits are not applied at all or are not applied under certain circumstances.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The phrase *bag limits* come from the custom among hunters of small game to carry successful kills in a small basket, similar to a fishing creel.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Where bag limits are used, there can be daily or seasonal bag limits; for example, ducks can often be harvested at a rate of six per hunter per day.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Big game, like moose, most often have a seasonal bag limit of one animal per hunter.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Bag limits may also regulate the size, sex, or age of animal that a hunter can kill.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In many cases, bag limits are designed to allocate harvest among the hunting population more equitably rather than to protect animal populations, as protecting the population would necessitate regional density-dependent maximum bags.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] A closed season is a time during which hunting an animal of a given species is contrary to law.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Typically, closed seasons are designed to protect a species when they are most vulnerable or to protect them during their breeding season.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] By extension, the period that is not the closed season is known as the open season.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Historical, subsistence, and sport hunting techniques can differ radically, with modern hunting regulations often addressing issues of where, when, and how hunts are conducted.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Techniques may vary depending on government regulations, a hunter's personal ethics, local custom, hunting equipment, and the animal being hunted.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Often a hunter will use a combination of more than one technique.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Laws may forbid sport hunters from using some methods used primarily in poaching and wildlife management.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Trophy hunting is the selective seeking and killing of wild game animals to take trophies for personal collection, bragging rights or as a status symbol.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] It may also include the controversial hunting of captive or semi-captive animals expressly bred and raised under controlled or semi-controlled conditions so as to attain trophy characteristics; this is sometimes known as canned hunts.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In the 19th century, southern and central European sport hunters often pursued game only for a trophy, usually the head or pelt of an animal, which was then displayed as a sign of prowess.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The rest of the animal was typically discarded.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Some cultures, however, disapprove of such waste.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In Nordic countries, hunting for trophies was—and still is—frowned upon.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunting in North America in the 19th century was done primarily as a way to supplement food supplies, although it is now undertaken mainly for sport.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The safari method of hunting was a development of sport hunting that saw elaborate travel in Africa, India and other places in pursuit of trophies.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] In modern times, trophy hunting persists and is a significant industry in some areas.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Trophy hunting has been considered essential for providing economic incentives to conserve large carnivores according to research studies in *Conservation Biology*, *Journal of Sustainable Tourism*, *Wildlife Conservation by Sustainable Use*, and *Animal Conservation*.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Studies by the Centre for Responsible Tourism and the IUCN state that ecotourism, which includes more than hunting, is a superior economic incentive, generating twice the revenue per acre and 39 times more permanent employment.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] At the cross-section of trophy hunting, ecotourism and conservation is green hunting, a trophy hunting alternative where hunters pay to dart animals that need to be tranquilized for conservation projects.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] House Committee on Natural Resources in 2016 concluded that trophy hunting may be contributing to the extinction of certain animals.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Animal welfare organizations, including the International Fund for Animal Welfare, claim that trophy hunting is a key factor in the "silent extinction" of giraffes.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] According to a national survey that the U.S.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Fish and Wildlife Service conducts every five years, fewer people are hunting, even as population rises.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] National Public Radio reported, a graph shows 2016 statistics, that only about 5 per cent of Americans, 16 years old and older, actually hunt, which is half of what it was 50 years ago.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] The decline in popularity of hunting is expected to accelerate over the next decade, which threatens how US will pay for conservation.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Trophy hunting is most often criticised when it involves rare or endangered animals.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Opponents may also see trophy hunting as an issue of morality or animal cruelty, criticising the killing of living creatures for recreation.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] There is also debate about the extent to which trophy hunting benefits the local economy.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] Hunters pay substantial fees to the game outfitters and hunting guides which contributes to the local economy and provides value to animals that would otherwise be seen as competition for grazing, livestock, and crops.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] However, the argument is disputed by animal welfare organizations and other opponents of trophy hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p01] It is argued that the animals are worth more to the community for ecotourism than hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] A variety of industries benefit from hunting and support hunting on economic grounds.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In Tanzania, it is estimated that a safari hunter spends fifty to one hundred times that of the average ecotourist.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] While the average photo tourist may seek luxury accommodation, the average safari hunter generally stays in tented camps.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Safari hunters are also more likely to use remote areas, uninviting to the typical ecotourist.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Advocates argue that these hunters allow for anti-poaching activities and revenue for local communities.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In the United Kingdom, the game hunting of birds as an industry is said to be extremely important to the rural economy.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The Cobham Report of 1997 suggested it to be worth around £700 million, and hunting and shooting lobby groups claimed it to be worth over a billion pounds less than ten years later.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Hunting also has a significant financial impact in the United States, with many companies specialising in hunting equipment or speciality tourism.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Many different technologies have been created to assist hunters.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Today's hunters come from a broad range of economic, social, and cultural backgrounds.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In 2001, over thirteen million hunters averaged eighteen days hunting, and spent over $20.5 billion on their sport.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In the US, proceeds from hunting licenses contribute to state game management programs, including preservation of wildlife habitat.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Hunting contributes to a portion of caloric intake of people and may have positive impacts on greenhouse gas emissions by avoidance of utilization of meat raised under industrial methods.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Lead bullets that miss their target or remain in an unretrieved carcass could become a toxicant in the environment but lead in ammunition because of its metallic form has a lower solubility and higher resistance to corrosion than other forms of lead making it hardly available to biological systems.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Waterfowl or other birds may ingest the lead and poison themselves with the neurotoxicant, but studies have demonstrated that effects of lead in ammunition are negligible on animal population size and growth.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Since 1991, US federal law forbids lead shot in waterfowl hunts, and 30 states have some type of restriction.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In December 2014, a federal appeals court denied a lawsuit by environmental groups that the EPA must use the Toxic Substances Control Act to regulate lead in shells and cartridges.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The groups sought EPA to regulate "spent lead", yet the court found EPA could not regulate spent lead without also regulating cartridges and shells.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Hunters have been driving forces throughout history in the movement to ensure the preservation of wildlife habitats and wildlife for further hunting.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] All these animals have been hunted to endangerment or extinction.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Poaching currently threatens bird and mammalian populations around the world.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The 2019 *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* lists the direct exploitation of organisms, including hunting, as the second leading cause of biodiversity loss, after land use for agriculture.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In 2022, IPBES released another report which stated that unsustainable hunting, along with unsustainable logging and fishing, are primary drivers of the global extinction crisis.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] A 2023 study published in *BioScience* posited that the prioritizing of hunting by state agencies in the United States over the rewinding of key species is "reinforcing" the loss of biodiversity.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In 1937, American hunters successfully lobbied the US Congress to pass the Pittman-Robertson Wildlife Restoration Act, which placed an eleven per cent tax on all hunting equipment.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] This self-imposed tax now generates over $700 million each year and is used exclusively to establish, restore and protect wildlife habitats.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The act is named for Nevada Senator Key Pittman and Virginia Congressman Absalom Willis Robertson.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Roosevelt signed the Migratory Bird Hunting Stamp Act, which requires an annual stamp purchase by all hunters over the age of sixteen.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The stamps are created on behalf of the program by the US Postal Service and depict wildlife artwork chosen through an annual contest.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] They play an important role in habitat conservation because ninety-eight per cent of all funds generated by their sale go directly toward the purchase or lease of wetland habitat for protection in the National Wildlife Refuge System.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In addition to waterfowl, it is estimated that one third of the nation's endangered species seek food and shelter in areas protected using Duck Stamp funds.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Since 1934, the sale of Federal Duck Stamps has generated $670 million, and helped to purchase or lease 5,200,000 acres (8,100 sq mi; 21,000 km2) of habitat.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The stamps serve as a license to hunt migratory birds, an entrance pass for all National Wildlife Refuge areas, and are also considered collector's items often purchased for aesthetic reasons outside of the hunting and birding communities.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Although non-hunters buy a significant number of Duck Stamps, eighty-seven per cent of their sales are contributed by hunters.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Distribution of funds is managed by the Migratory Bird Conservation Commission (MBCC).
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The Arabian oryx, a species of large antelope, once inhabited much of the desert areas of the Middle East.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Native Bedouin tribes had long hunted the oryx using camels and arrows.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Oil exploration made the habitat increasingly accessible, and the species' striking appearance made it (along with the closely related scimitar-horned oryx and addax) a popular quarry for sport hunters, including foreign executives of oil companies.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The use of automobiles and high-powered rifles destroyed their only advantage: speed, and they became extinct in the wild exclusively due to sport hunting in 1972.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The scimitar-horned oryx followed suit, while the addax became critically endangered.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] However, the Arabian oryx has now made a comeback and been upgraded from "extinct in the wild" to "vulnerable" due to conservation efforts like captive breeding.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The markhor is an endangered species of wild goat which inhabits the mountains of Central Asia and Pakistan.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The colonization of these regions by Britain gave British sport hunters access to the species, and they were hunted heavily, almost to the point of extinction.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Only their willingness to breed in captivity and the inhospitability of their mountainous habitat prevented this.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Despite these factors, the markhor is still endangered.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The American bison is a large bovid which inhabited much of western North America prior to the 1800s, living on the prairies in large herds.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] However, the vast herds of bison attracted market hunters, who killed dozens of bison for their hides only, leaving the rest to rot.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Thousands of these hunters quickly eliminated the bison herds, bringing the population from several million in the early 1800s to a few hundred by the 1880s.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Conservation efforts have allowed the population to increase, but the bison remains near-threatened due to lack of habitat.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The *Journal of International Wildlife Law and Policy* cites that the legalization of white rhinoceros hunting in South Africa motivated private landowners to reintroduce the species onto their lands.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] As a result, the country saw an increase in white rhinos from fewer than one hundred individuals to more than 11,000, even while a limited number were killed as trophies.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] However, the illegal hunting of rhinoceros for their horns is highly damaging to the population and is currently growing globally, with 1004 being killed in South Africa alone according to the most recent estimate.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The White Rhino (along with the other 4 rhino species) are poached due to beliefs that the Rhinos' horns can be used to cure cancer, arthritis, and other diseases and illnesses, even though they are scientifically proven wrong.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] According to Richard Conniff, Namibia is home to 1,750 of the roughly 5,000 black rhinos surviving in the wild because it allows trophy hunting of various species.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Namibia's mountain zebra population has increased to 27,000 from 1,000 in 1982.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Elephants, which "are gunned down elsewhere for their ivory", have gone to 20,000 from 15,000 in 1995.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Lions, which were on the brink of extinction "from Senegal to Kenya", are increasing in Namibia.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In contrast, Botswana in 2012 banned trophy hunting following a precipitous wildlife decline.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The numbers of antelope plummeted across Botswana, with a resultant decline in predator numbers, while elephant numbers remained stable and hippopotamus numbers rose.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] According to the government of Botswana, trophy hunting is at least partly to blame for this, but many other factors, such as poaching, drought and habitat loss are also to blame.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Uganda recently did the same, arguing that "the share of benefits of sport hunting were lopsided and unlikely to deter poaching or improve [Uganda's] capacity to manage the wildlife reserves." In 2020, Botswana reopened trophy hunting on public lands.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] A study published by the Wildlife Society concluded that hunting and trapping are cost effective tools that reduce wildlife damage by reducing a population below the capacity of the environment to carry it and changing the behaviors of animals to stop them from causing damage.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] The study furthermore states that the cessation of hunting could cause wildlife to be severely harmed, rural property values to fall, and the incentive of landowners to maintain natural habitats to diminish.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Animal rights activists argue that killing animals for sport is unethical, cruel, and unnecessary.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] They note the suffering and cruelty inflicted on animals hunted for sport: "Many animals endure prolonged, painful deaths when they are injured but not killed by hunters.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Hunting disrupts migration and hibernation patterns and destroys families." Animal rights activists also comment that hunting is not needed to maintain an ecological balance, and that "nature takes care of its own".
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] They say that hunting can be combated on public lands by "spread[ing] deer repellent or human hair (from barber shops) near hunting areas".
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In Vietnam, Singapore, China, Brunei, hunting is almost entirely illegal.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Except for aquatic and marine products, insects and rodents, amphibians, and some reptiles such as snakes and lizards.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In China, after 2020, hunting as a livelihood for ethnic minorities almost disappeared due to the ban on consuming bushmeat.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In Vietnam, although nominally some non-endangered species in group IIIA can be hunted with permits and forest owners, in reality no permits are issued.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Some destructive species like sparrows and squirrels were previously overlooked by the government, but recently, regulations have been tightened.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] Although hunting some reptiles like sand lizards is illegal, the government considers it legal.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] A similar situation previously occurred with wild birds; many Vietnamese people consider wild birds as a resource to be exploited rather than a priority for conservation.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In one survey, although many people claimed they rarely or never consumed wild animals, when asked if they had eaten egrets or herons, they were surprised.
[src:hunting/hunting-p02] In Singapore, even frogs are considered wild animals.
